1 have gone through these expedients at some length, partly because they are an instructive illustration of medieval finance, partly because they specify the resources which the country possessed at the time. There was, the times considered, abundance of wealth in England at the period immediately preceding the outbrealr of civil war. The fifteenth century was a period of singularly unbroken agricultural prosperity, of plentiful harvests, of high wages, of accumulated opulence. Land which 3 century before yielded in rent a return of ten per cent. on the purchase money, now yielded five or less. Farmers were gradually acquiring free· hold estates 3ηά becoming yeomen, were the progenitors of the small gentry who played so conspicuous a part in English History two cen- turies later. In the universal passion for acquiring land commons were enclosed, often by usurpation, and men of free estate became the pur· chasers of copyhold, thus giving stability and a higher position to those ‘estates which the law books still affected to call base or precarious.
